description.plain:
Marvin William Bailey (b. March 4th 1994), professionally known as Fredo, is a rapper and entrepreneur hailing from Mozart Estate, Harrow Road in Queen’s Park, West London.

He was noted as being a prominent figure in the Harrow Road Boyz gang based in West London. Taking on a raw flow & style in his music, reflecting on his drug dealing, criminal lifestyle and poverty-based background, Fredo has become one of the most exciting and crucial parts of the UK music scene.

Fredo burst onto the scene in January of 2016 with his first song “They Ain’t 100”. Going to prison just three-weeks later, it was whilst he was sat in jail that the track started to blow up with various radio play, racking up millions of views on YouTube and becoming a notorious street-anthem that’ll eventually put him on the map. Inspired to see where his music could take him, after beating his charge, he seemed to have found his calling. He struggled in leaving the street life behind him and ended up in prison for the second time for a firearm charge. It was in prison where he announced his first mixtape Get Rich Or Get Recalled, which dropped on the 17th of March 2017.

Fredo’s second mixtape Tables Turn dropped on the 9th of February 2018. The project had his return anthem “Change”, and stand-out single “Rappin' & Trappin'”. The mixtape peaked at Number 5 on the UK Charts and is certified Silver. He also had a leading feature alongside Young T & Bugsey on Stay Flee Get Lizzy’s debut single “Ay Caramba”, giving him his first taste of chart success, landing on the UK Top 40 at Number 36.

Before 2018 had ended, Fredo featured on South London rapper Dave’s hit-single “Funky Friday” which went on to become a commercial success, debuting at Number 1 on the UK Charts – becoming Fredo’s first as well as the first song by a British rapper to reach the top position, serving as a significant moment for British rap music.

Third Avenue served as Fredo’s debut studio album and came out on February 1st 2019. The lead singles for this album featured tracks “BMT” and “All I Ever Wanted”. The album peaked at Number 5 on the UK Charts.

Throughout the rest of 2019, Fredo dropped a string of singles and features, including a big collaboration with Birmingham rapper MIST on the track “So High”, which peaked at Number 7 on the UK Charts. Fredo also dropped his single “Netflix and Chill” which entered the UK Top 20 Charts and featured on Stay Flee Get Lizzy’s party banger “2 Cups” with Tory Lanez and Popcaan. Fredo dropped his highly anticipated Daily Duppy in August 2020.

On the 20th of January 2021, Fredo announced his sophomore studio album Money Can’t Buy Happiness, which was released on the 29th alongside the singles “Back to Basics” and “Money Talks” with Dave, which debut at Number 2 on the UK Charts.

In April 2021, Fredo made a huge business venture as he announced a mutli-million pound investment into UK sneaker chain Kick Game, becoming a partial owner. In June 2021, Fredo announced his third studio album Independence Day, set to release in July of the same year.

songs.title: Money Talks

description.plain:
“Money Talks,” the third single from Money Can’t Buy Happiness, was released on the day before the drop of the album. The track marks Fredo’s third collaboration with South London rap sensation Dave, who also produced this track and executively produced the album.

On the cut, Fredo and Dave go back-and-forth questioning their opposition, asking if the opps even deserve to be in the same conversation as the rap duo when they aren’t even in the same tax bracket.

description.plain:
On “Burner On Deck”, Fredo calls in two features in the form of D-Block Europe frontman Young Adz and late New York drill artist Pop Smoke.

On a hazy bass-heavy beat produced by Yoz Beatz and RicoRunDat, Young Adz melodically rides the chorus' wave as Fredo and Pop Smoke drift along their signature flows as the trio explore topics such as their firearms, the money they made off the trap, the fear they struck into their opp’s – all whilst living their lavish lifestyles.

If the intro of the album tells us anything about him, it’s that his money can’t buy his happiness.

songs.title: Freestyle

description.plain:
Independence Day Freestyle was dropped as a surpise with no promotion on the 6th of May, and serves as the first track by West London rapper Fredo following his critical and commercially acclaimed sophomore studio album Money Can’t Buy Happiness released in January 2021.

Though unconfirmed, Fredo dropped a cryptic message of “Independence Day is coming” – which was thought to be the teased collab mixtape with Church Road, North London rapper Nines. On the 24th of June, Fredo announced his third studio album Independence Day, set to be released in July 2021.

Going back to his patented expensive flow, Freddy details his former life of being poor, a drug dealer and gangbanger whilst also issuing a warning to his opp’s as he “still has ties with the streets”. In contrast, also boasts about his newfound millions and brazenly raps about his multi-million pound diamond chains and watches. This is Fredo back in his element.

songs.title: Ready

description.plain:
On “Ready”, the fourth track on Money Can’t Buy Happiness, Fredo calls in a big feature from Atlanta singer/songwriter Summer Walker.

Though still speaking on waging war against his opp’s and bragging about his vast wealth, Fredo marks this as an triumphant victory lap of his life and career, speaking on the wrong he’s done in his life and his plans to rectify them – all bridged together perfectly with Summer Walker’s bouncy chorus and vocal work.

Fredo also makes multiple references to ‘Billy’, a.k.a ‘Billy Da Kid’, who was shot and killed in July 2020 by rival gang members. Billy belonged to the same gang as Fredo (Harrow Road Boys). He has been mentioned before in the track “Survival of the Fittest” as ‘Bad Luck Billy’.

description.plain:
“Blood In My Eyes”, Fredo’s ninth cut on Money Can’t Buy Happiness, he keeps the theme of vulnerability and being open in his music. Specifically touching on the birth of his daughter, his relationship with his daughter’s mother, growing up in a rough estate,  and his mental state after being through what he’s seen.

The track samples Hozier’s Arsonist’s Lullaby.
